125
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:21,840
- Hello, Synthesizer Patel.
- Hi, Pealy.

126
00:08:21,880 --> 00:08:25,715
Synthesizer Patel, synthesizers
are really taking off, aren't they?

127
00:08:25,760 --> 00:08:29,356
Oh, yes, Pealy. Every pop group
wants a synthesizer these days

128
00:08:29,400 --> 00:08:33,553
because a synthesizer can reproduce
the sound of any instrument,

129
00:08:33,600 --> 00:08:36,957
except perhaps for the bassoon
but they're working on that one.

130
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,356
But they can do more
than that, can't they?

131
00:08:39,400 --> 00:08:42,632
Oh, certainly. This is something
that might interest you.

132
00:08:44,160 --> 00:08:48,074
OK, so what I did earlier was
I made recording of my own voice

133
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:50,476
- using this microphone.
- Mm-hm.

134
00:08:50,520 --> 00:08:54,070
And I stored that data into
the synthesizer's memory banks.

135
00:08:54,120 --> 00:08:56,191
And now here is the fun bit.

136
00:08:56,240 --> 00:08:58,232
I can play back to you.

137
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:05,395
